article.description: Michael Kuebler scored 28 points, leading Hawaii to an 85-74 victory over Utah State in the first round of the NIT on Wednesday night.
article.headline: Kuebler's 28 make for pleasant mainland visit
article.linkText: Snubbed, then drubbed: Hawaii rolls Utah State
article.story: LOGAN, Utah -- Michael Kuebler and Hawaii were not intimidated by facing the only ranked team in the NIT. Kuebler scored 28 points to lead Hawaii to an 85-74 victory over No. 25 Utah State in the first round on Wednesday night. "It was the last game of the year if you lose," said Kuebler, who was just one point shy of his career high. "We came into the game tonight thinking that they were the No. 1 seeded team in the tournament." The Warriors (20-11), who had lost three straight and seven of their last 10, scored their first-ever road win over a ranked opponent. In the second round, they will play the winner of Friday's Nebraska-Niagara game. Hawaii shot 62 percent (34-for-55) and had four players score in double figures, including Jeff Blackett's 18 points as a reserve. Jason Carter had 13 for Hawaii and Julian Sensley scored 12. Utah State could not muster the defensive energy to shut down the Hawaii offense, and found little spark in its own offense. In the first half, Hawaii had two 9-0 scoring runs. USU coach Stew Morrill, whose team went undefeated at home during the regular season, said the Aggies couldn't find a way to shut down Kuebler or Blackett. "He (Kuebler) was amazing tonight and is a heck of a player," Morrill said. "I can see how he averaged 18 points in that league (the Western Athletic Conference). He shot over us, around us, went by us -- we didn't have anyone that could do much with him." Kuebler went 4-for-6 from 3-point range and 10-of-17 overall. He said USU had not seen any WAC teams and might not have been as familiar with Hawaii's shooting style, and that led to more open shots. Utah State guard Cardell Butler said the difference was oomph. They had more energy than we did," Butler said. "They should have been tired (after their 17-hour trip), not us." Blackett agreed the game came down to energy. "After the WAC tournament, we weren't sure if our season was going to continue or not, but we had some time to get our legs back under us," Blackett said. Hawaii went 8-of-13 from three-point range and 9-of-11 from the free-throw line. Utah State's Spencer Nelson had a double-double with a career-high 24 points and 11 rebounds. Cardell Butler added 15 points and Mike Ahmad and Mark Brown each had 11 for the Aggies. This is the second time in three years USU has lost in the first round of the NIT. Utah State has not won an NIT game since the 1960 season, when the Aggies beat Villanova 73-72.
